Use ASP.NET Core's **`WebApplicationFactory<T>`** — it hosts your app in-memory and gives you an `HttpClient` that talks to it without opening a real port.

### Setup

```bash
dotnet add package Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing
dotnet add package xunit
```

### Example test

```csharp
using System.Net.Http.Json;
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing;
using Xunit;

public class McpIntegrationTests
    : IClassFixture<WebApplicationFactory<Program>>
{
    private readonly HttpClient _client;

    public McpIntegrationTests(WebApplicationFactory<Program> factory)
    {
        _client = factory.CreateClient();
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task Initialize_ReturnsServerCapabilities()
    {
        var request = new
        {
            jsonrpc = "2.0",
            id = 1,
            method = "initialize",
            @params = new
            {
                protocolVersion = "2025-03-26",
                capabilities = new { },
                clientInfo = new { name = "test-client", version = "1.0" }
            }
        };

        var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);

        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        var body = await response.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>();
        Assert.Equal("2025-03-26",
            body.GetProperty("result")
                .GetProperty("protocolVersion")
                .GetString());
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task ToolsCall_ExecutesTool()
    {
        // Initialize first (required by MCP)
        await InitializeSession();

        var request = new
        {
            jsonrpc = "2.0",
            id = 2,
            method = "tools/call",
            @params = new
            {
                name = "my_tool",
                arguments = new { input = "hello" }
            }
        };

        var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);

        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        var body = await response.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>();
        Assert.False(body.GetProperty("result")
                        .GetProperty("isError")
                        .GetBoolean());
    }

    private async Task InitializeSession() { /* send initialize + initialized */ }
}
```

### Key points

| Technique | Why |
|---|---|
| `WebApplicationFactory<Program>` | Hosts your full pipeline (middleware, DI, routing) in-process — no port, no process spawn |
| `factory.WithWebHostBuilder(b => ...)` | Override services (e.g., swap a database for an in-memory fake) |
| `factory.CreateClient()` | Returns an `HttpClient` wired to the in-memory server |

### If you need to mock dependencies

```csharp
var factory = new WebApplicationFactory<Program>()
    .WithWebHostBuilder(builder =>
    {
        builder.ConfigureServices(services =>
        {
            // Replace a real service with a test double
            services.RemoveAll<IMyExternalService>();
            services.AddSingleton<IMyExternalService, FakeExternalService>();
        });
    });
```

### If your server uses SSE (Streamable HTTP)

For endpoints returning `text/event-stream`, read the stream incrementally:

```csharp
var response = await _client.SendAsync(request,
    HttpCompletionOption.ResponseHeadersRead);
using var stream = await response.Content.ReadAsStreamAsync();
using var reader = new StreamReader(stream);

while (await reader.ReadLineAsync() is { } line)
{
    // parse SSE frames: "data: {...}"
}
```

This gives you full-fidelity MCP protocol testing — real HTTP, real middleware, real routing — with the speed of an in-process call.
